figure>
<p>A <b>scientific calculator</b> is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Electronics" title=3D"Electronics">electronic</a> <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculator" title=3D"Calculator">calculator</a>, eith=
er desktop or handheld, designed to perform calculations using basic (<a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addition" title=3D"Addition">addition</=
a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subtraction" title=3D"Subtract=
ion">subtraction</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplicati=
on" title=3D"Multiplication">multiplication</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Division_(mathematics)" title=3D"Division (mathematics)">div=
ision</a>) and advanced (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonome=
tric_functions" title=3D"Trigonometric functions">trigonometric</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions" title=3D"Hyperboli=
c functions">hyperbolic</a>, etc.) mathematical <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Operation_(mathematics)" title=3D"Operation (mathematics)">op=
erations</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathema=
tics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">functions</a>. They have completely=
 replaced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slide_rule" title=3D"Sli=
de rule">slide rules</a> as well as books of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mathematical_table" title=3D"Mathematical table">mathematical ta=
bles</a> and are used in both educational and professional settings.
</p><p>In some areas of study and professions scientific calculators have b=
een replaced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphing_calculato=
r" title=3D"Graphing calculator">graphing calculators</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_calculator" title=3D"Financial calcul=
ator">financial calculators</a> which have the capabilities of a scientific=
 calculator along with the capability to graph input data and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (math=
ematics)">functions</a>, as well as by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Numerical_computing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Numerical computin=
g">numerical computing</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comput=
er_algebra" title=3D"Computer algebra">computer algebra</a>, statistical, a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spreadsheet" title=3D"Spreadshe=
et">spreadsheet</a> software packages running on <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Personal_computer" title=3D"Personal computer">personal comp=
uters</a>. Both desktop and mobile <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Software_calculator" title=3D"Software calculator">software calculators</a=
> can also emulate many functions of a physical scientific calculator. Stan=
dalone scientific calculators remain popular in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Secondary_education" title=3D"Secondary education">secondary<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tertiary_education" title=
=3D"Tertiary education">tertiary education</a> because computers and smartp=
hones are often prohibited during exams to reduce the likelihood of cheatin=
g.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Scientific_calculator#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Functions">Functions</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DScientific_calcula=
tor&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Functions"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<p>When <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_calculators" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electronic calculators">electronic calculators=
</a> were originally marketed they normally had only four or five capabilit=
ies (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addition" title=3D"Addition">=
addition</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subtraction" title=
=3D"Subtraction">subtraction</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Multiplication" title=3D"Multiplication">multiplication</a>, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(military)" title=3D"Division (military=
)">division</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_root" t=
itle=3D"Square root">square root</a>). Modern scientific calculators genera=
lly have many more capabilities than the original four- or five-function ca=
lculator, and the capabilities differ between manufacturers and models.=20
</p><p>The capabilities of a modern scientific calculator include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation" title=
=3D"Scientific notation">Scientific notation</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floating-point_arithmetic" tit=
le=3D"Floating-point arithmetic">Floating-point decimal arithmetic</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm"=
>Logarithmic</a> functions, using both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Common_logarithm" title=3D"Common logarithm">base 10</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_logarithm" title=3D"Natural logar=
ithm">base <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</spa=
n></a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometry" title=3D"Trigono=
metry">Trigonometric</a> functions (some including <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hyperb=
olic function">hyperbolic trigonometry</a>)</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponent" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Exponent">Exponential</a> functions and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Nth_root" title=3D"Nth root">roots</a> beyond the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_root" title=3D"Square root">square=
 root</a></li>
<li>Quick access to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_c=
onstant" title=3D"Mathematical constant">constants</a> such as <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pi" title=3D"Pi"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span></a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/E_(mathematical_constant)" title=3D"E (mathematical consta=
nt)"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span></a>=
</li></ul>
<p>In addition, high-end scientific calculators generally include some or a=
ll of the following:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cursor_(user_interface)" t=
itle=3D"Cursor (user interface)">Cursor</a> controls to edit <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equation" title=3D"Equation">equations</a> and v=
iew previous calculations (some calculators such as the <i>LCD-8310</i>, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Badge_engineered" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Badge engineered">badge engineered</a> under both <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOlympia_Business_Systems&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Olympia Business S=
ystems (page does not exist)">Olympia</a></i> and <i><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DUnited_Office&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redli=
nk=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"United Office (page does not exist)">United =
Office</a></i> keep the number of the previous result on-screen for conveni=
ence while the new calculation is being entered.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_calcula=
tor#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>)</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexadecimal" title=3D"Hexadeci=
mal">Hexadecimal</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_numer=
al_system" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Binary numeral system">binary</a>=
, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal" title=3D"Octal">octal=
</a> calculations, including basic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Boolean_logic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Boolean logic">Boolean</a> m=
athematics</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_numbers" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Complex numbers">Complex numbers</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction_(mathematics)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fraction (mathematics)">Fractions</a> calculation=
s</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistic=
s">Statistics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability"=
 title=3D"Probability">probability</a> calculations</li>
<li>Programmability =E2=80=94 see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Programmable_calculator" title=3D"Programmable calculator">Programmable cal=
culator</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equation_solving" title=3D"Equ=
ation solving">Equation solving</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Computer_algebra" title=3D"Computer algebra">computer algebra</a></li=
>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D=
"Matrix (mathematics)">Matrix calculations</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">C=
alculus</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Letter_(alphabet)" title=3D"Le=
tter (alphabet)">Letters</a> that can be used for spelling words or includi=
ng <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Variable (mathematics)">variables</a> into an equation</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conversion_of_units" title=3D"=
Conversion of units">Conversion of units</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_constants" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Physical constants">Physical constants</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_(mathematics_and_physic=
s)" title=3D"Vector (mathematics and physics)">Vector calculations</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation" titl=
e=3D"Random number generation">Random number generation</a></li></ul>
<p>While most scientific calculators have traditionally used a single-line =
display similar to traditional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poc=
ket_calculators" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pocket calculators">pocket =
calculators</a>, many of them have more digits (10 to 12), sometimes with e=
xtra digits for the floating-point exponent.  A few have multi-line display=
s, with some models from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hewlett-P=
ackard" title=3D"Hewlett-Packard">Hewlett-Packard</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Texas_Instruments" title=3D"Texas Instruments">Texas I=
nstruments</a> (both US manufacturers), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Casio" title=3D"Casio">Casio</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Sharp_Corporation" title=3D"Sharp Corporation">Sharp</a>, and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canon_(company)" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Canon (company)">Canon</a> (all three Japanese makers) using <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_matrix" title=3D"Dot matrix">dot matr=
ix</a> displays similar to those found on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Graphing_calculator" title=3D"Graphing calculator">graphing calcula=
tors</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Uses">Uses</h2><span class=
