t-matrix area can display input formulae and symbols.<br> <i>Right:</i> The=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TI-84_Plus_series" title=3D"TI-84=
 Plus series">TI-84 Plus</a>=E2=80=94a typical graphing calculator by Texas=
 Instruments</div></div></div></div>
<p>Scientific calculators are used widely in situations that require quick =
access to certain mathematical functions, especially those that were once l=
ooked up in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_table" ti=
tle=3D"Mathematical table">mathematical tables</a>, such as <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometric_functions" title=3D"Trigonometric f=
unctions">trigonometric functions</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithms</a>, or <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability distrib=
ution">probability distributions</a>.  They are also used for calculations =
of very large or very small numbers, as in some aspects of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomy" title=3D"Astronomy">astronomy</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a>=
, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemistry" title=3D"Chemistr=
y">chemistry</a>.
</p><p>They are very often required for math classes from the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Junior_High_School" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Junior High School">junior high school</a> level through <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/College" title=3D"College">college</a>,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Scientific_calculator#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and are generally either pe=
rmitted or required on many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standa=
rdized_test" title=3D"Standardized test">standardized tests</a> covering ma=
th and science subjects;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_calculator#cite_note-4"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> as a result, many are sold into educational markets to cover this dema=
nd, and some high-end models include features making it easier to translate=
 a problem on a textbook page into calculator input, e.g. by providing a me=
thod to enter an entire problem in as it is written on the page using simpl=
e formatting tools.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DScientific_calculator&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:HP-35_Red_Dot.jpg" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commo=
ns/thumb/3/34/HP-35_Red_Dot.jpg/250px-HP-35_Red_Dot.jpg" decoding=3D"async"=
 width=3D"250" height=3D"417" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"=
1530" data-file-height=3D"2550"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/HP-35" title=3D"HP-35">HP-35</a>, the world's first scientifi=
c pocket calculator, was introduced in 1972 by Hewlett-Packard. It used <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reverse_Polish_notation" title=3D"Rev=
erse Polish notation">reverse Polish notation</a> and an <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LED" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"LED">LED</a> dis=
play.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Texas_Instruments_SR-50.jpg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/5/50/Texas_Instruments_SR-50.jpg/250px-Texas_Instruments_SR-50.jpg" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"437" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"3099" data-file-height=3D"5418"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TI_SR-50" title=3D"TI SR-50">TI SR-50</a></fig=
caption></figure>
<p>The first scientific calculator that included all of the basic ideas abo=
ve was the programmable Hewlett-Packard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Hewlett-Packard_9100A" title=3D"Hewlett-Packard 9100A">HP-9100A</a>,<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Scientific_calculator#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> released in 1968, tho=
ugh the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wang_Laboratories" title=
=3D"Wang Laboratories">Wang</a> LOCI-2 and the Mathatronics Mathatron<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Scientific_calculator#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> had some features later id=
entified with scientific calculator designs. The HP-9100 series was built e=
ntirely from discrete <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transistor" =
title=3D"Transistor">transistor</a> logic with no <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Integrated_circuit" title=3D"Integrated circuit">integrated=
 circuits</a>, and was one of the first uses of the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/CORDIC" title=3D"CORDIC">CORDIC</a> algorithm for trigono=
metric computation in a personal computing device, as well as the first cal=
culator based on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reverse_Polish_no=
tation" title=3D"Reverse Polish notation">reverse Polish notation</a> (RPN)=
 entry. HP became closely identified with RPN calculators from then on, and=
 even today some of their high-end calculators (particularly the long-lived=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HP-12C" title=3D"HP-12C">HP-12C</=
a> financial calculator and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HP=
-48" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"HP-48">HP-48</a> series of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphing_calculator" title=3D"Graphing calcula=
tor">graphing calculators</a>) still offer RPN as their default input mode =
due to having garnered a very large following.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HP-35" title=3D"HP-35">=
HP-35</a>, introduced on February 1, 1972, was Hewlett-Packard's first <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pocket_calculator" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Pocket calculator">pocket calculator</a> and the world's first =
handheld scientific calculator.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_calculator#cite_note-7">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> Like some of HP's desktop calculators it used RPN. Introduced at=
 US$395, the HP-35 was available from 1972 to 1975.
</p><p>Texas Instruments (TI), after the production of several units with <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation" title=3D"Scien=
tific notation">scientific notation</a>, introduced a handheld scientific c=
alculator on January 15, 1974, in the form of the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/TI_SR-50" title=3D"TI SR-50">SR-50</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_=
calculator#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> TI's long-running <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/TI-30" title=3D"TI-30">TI-30</a> series being one of t=
he most widely used scientific calculators in classrooms.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casio" title=3D"Casio">Casi=
o</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canon_Inc." title=3D"Canon =
Inc.">Canon</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharp_Corpora=
tion" title=3D"Sharp Corporation">Sharp</a>, produced their   graphing  cal=
culators, with Casio's FX series (beginning with the Casio FX-1 in 1972<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Scientific_calculator#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>). Casio was the first co=
mpany to produce a Graphing calculator (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Casio_fx-7000G" title=3D"Casio fx-7000G">Casio fx-7000G</a>).
</p>
